Turkey Expands Diplomatic Horizon
Long before Turkey aspired to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in invading deeply into Turkey’s hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps inside Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the guides tell you.
The building sits idly at the end of the platforms with a tower on each corner of the front and looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building collapsed.
But once you are inside the vaulted ticket counter, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose westernmost access was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Society.
Germany, which was a scavenger in the imperialist game, had before its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperialist plans paralyzed during the First World War.
His railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces pulled out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha train station.
In 1917, a munitions train flew into the air, destroying the artificial roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, largely transitioned from history.
Today, however, this railway line, at least symbolically, serves as a gateway to Anatolia and everything to the east of it, to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the ACP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighboring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key data of this new foreign policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital of Ankara to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the equal footing of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is seen as a new city, for the new secular state project, to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has sparked a lot of mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the main ACP office, a custom-built, ultra-modern stone and steel construction, in a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy objective is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception,” he told me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it has to look east and west at the same time.
There would be no one or the other.
You'd have to do both.
“But surely at some point,” I asked, “Turkey might be forced to make a decision?”
“Turkey,” he said, “would not have to face this decision.”
He then pointed out a point that almost everyone I spoke to here almost routinely renounced: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, so the message seems to be, in the transmitted sense, Europe as a whole can travel on those flat railways eastwards towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha’s station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German dominions, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in Turkey’s hands.
And when I waited at the dock for the ferry to take me back across the Bosporus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At least at that time there seemed to be little doubt as to which continent should have a claim to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Death" Handley (pronounced 11 September) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Chorus.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was meant for teenagers up to 21 years old, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already in our late 20s - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological form changer) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to attack any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and was solely due to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music that never subsided for years.
How often did death keep us from "letting the music speak for itself".
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
Sing it!"
His way of directing was absolutely clear and precise, never overpowering but never overpowering.
No matter how high the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been beaten to the knight, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years or so, I’ve written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can honestly say that I’ve never been disappointed by a single one — often I was inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of size and personal modesty.
He denounced conductors who, according to him, simply "housed one or two known sheep horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your affidavit for William Woodruff (September 25), you write that "he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford in 1946 and received a Houblon-Norman research scholarship in 1950 ... while at the same time studying for a BSc, an MA, and a PhD.
This is a conclusion from an author's comment in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it is not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was in the United States from 1950 to 1951 on a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
