<0x60>Car-bees' that avoid collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was this time inspired by nature, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarming behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers from Nissan Motor Co.’s Technical Development Center developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology PR and R&D Brand Management, the BR23C is an extension of Nissan’s four-layer safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped airspace, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see over an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows it to fly undisturbed in its personal airspace without interruption.
To replicate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He notices obstacles in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and in a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is translated directly into a signal to avoid collision
The moment an obstacle is spotted, the small robot will mimic the bee’s flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at 90 degrees or even greater angles to avoid collision.
The biggest difference to other arbitrary systems is that this evasion maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not, the robot might not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory for Mobility and the senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can not deviate either upwards or downwards, but also not overhead; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in the infinite way that the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
<0x60>This device only needs a couple of seconds to process the information and act on that information.
It does not require storing the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a couple of dozen KB of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it’s not about the GBs or even the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in the next ten years at the production cars.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide you to your destination while avoiding obstacles along the way.
