Morgan Stanley makes its capital available to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, making it the first bank in Japan to spend nine billion dollars and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation that is due to a strong fall in its exchange rate.
A week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks stated that MUFG will buy 9.9% of the Morgan Stanley stock at a single price of $25.25, resulting in a total of $3 billion.
The assumed price is below 19% of the stock's price value on August 31.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a profit of 10% and can be resold at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be done on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, which is 28% above the current exchange rate.
However, the Morgan Stanley stock fell by 6.79% to $23.07 at 17.00 GMT.
“This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to the status of a holding bank,” said John Mack, CEO of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which should allow it to expand its business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection to MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The terms and conditions presented on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the past few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply stated that she would sell up to 20% of her shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” MUFG Managing Director Toshihide Mizuno said in Tokyo, “we thought the stake would consist entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.”
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its price value for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will pay off with a reduction in profit of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred shares into common shares in a year if the latter are exchanged at more than 50% above the sale value within a given period, i.e. at about $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will enable it to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its sales.
However, a spokesman for the group refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After investing in MUFG, Morgan Stanley should be able to book a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan stated that since the end of August, his balance sheet had “significantly” decreased.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group, which had to watch their stock market price fall by half as the price of insolvency insurance accelerated to the level.
This price fell on Monday, but remained at a high level, at around 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of major Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had withdrawn $15 billion, in part, from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Re-establishing the Republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
That third was the one who, following the example of his like-minded people and friends, put the plan for a new constitution to the vote this Sunday.
According to the public results of 80% of the vote, 64% voted ‘yes’ in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% agreed with ‘no’, 7% of ballots were invalid and 0.7% were empty.
In order for the draft constitution to be passed, one vote must be obtained by more than half of all votes cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exits of the polling stations and a census of a non-governmental organization had announced a clear victory for “yes” and predicted him 63% to 70%.
On the night of Sunday to Monday, Rafael Correa, by the way, had demanded the victory of his draft constitution.
The “constitution has triumphed in an overwhelming way,” he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Ecuadorians.
Of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held in silence according to the Observer Order of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to secure the “new socialism” for which the president is advocating.
The draft constitution transfers state power to the economy, leaving it the sole right to “development planning” in a country that largely lives off the oil production by foreign companies and the currencies that send expats to the country.
The project, which is driven by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the head of state more power, which will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
