The 19 hostages were freed in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions, who had been captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held captive in the desert for 11 days, were safely and unharmed returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were liberated by an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached al-Maza military base right next to Cairo International Airport at around 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, on board a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a foreign neighborhood of Cairo, to be examined there.
They enjoy all the "best health" and the kidnappers "were not paid ransom," Egypt's tourism minister Zoheir Garanna said on the pitch.
After being captured on 19 September during an off-road safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken by 35 unknown kidnappers from one hiding place to the next.
They are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, from two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
“On both sides shots fell and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,” said the official, who wants to remain anonymous.
He stated that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomats Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade where he is now, about the role played by the secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
“We have to acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence and special forces,” he said.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The day before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have stopped a ground vehicle during a patrol, in which the kidnappers were located, six of whom were killed, including the leader from Chad, and two arrested.
The army stated that they would be in contact with a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), which immediately disputed this movement.
