Benelux Governments National Parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux states want to take the arms of the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has fallen into turmoil due to the US financial crisis: The three states provide a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the Banking and Insurance Institute, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands consulted at the highest level this weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner of the European Commission's Competition Authority.
In the euro area, Fortis is the first victim of the ongoing international financial market crisis in a year, so decisions that are now being taken in relation to the bank could be precedent-setting.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank at about 49 percent.
The bank is likely to sell some of its holdings, most notably the insurance activities purchased by the Dutch company ABN Amro last year.
Fortis shares began a steep downhill run last week, with serious crisis scenarios already set in in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank with its 85,000 employees is far too big for a bankruptcy.
The Institute’s securities fell 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the Group’s market value is EUR 14 billion, which, according to management, is unrealistic.
According to management, the $700 billion costly U.S. bailout package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets is to blame for the downturn in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, prices rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new CEO.
The money institution was also looking for a private buyer, but there was no interested party with a factual offer.
The Belgian government, however, was trying to calm down - no investor should tremble for his money, it was said.
No panic has broken out among customers so far, the bank’s branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fuchs in the chicken coop
Because of a person’s drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to enter into a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are privacy programs that link the use of the drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we trust the fox the chickens," Richard Dick, the developer of the prescription data tracking program, quoted the Washington Post as saying.
Insurances determine the fees as well as the payout amounts in case of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and should the risk be overestimated, the insurance will not be completed at all.
Previously, the customer was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in knowledge of the examination results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: using the customer's identification number, he retrieves the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, that is, which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates from what disease the customer suffers and how his health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood fat levels are untreatably high, which would automatically place him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so the insurance companies only need to do more paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the drawbacks is that many medications can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is a high-risk factor from the insurer’s point of view, while the ones mentioned above are not.
For the query and processing of the data have formed their own companies, which, before obtaining the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not been punished so far.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with data on drug use to provide an even more accurate picture of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to the data, and controlling its use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect extends only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard understands that this is not enough, so he wants to develop his program so that the data can only be shared with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the data subject can hardly forbid access to his data, since insurance companies do not otherwise conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are just kind of left to the grace of the fox.
Global meal plan from Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this was the main topic among other global issues at the ninth summit.
Today, the Franco-Indian summit is also taking place, where cooperation in the nuclear energy sector is mainly discussed.
While the European Union recognises that India is an emerging, democratic major power that should be given more votes and the right to speak on international issues, the member states have so far been unable to agree on whether or not to support New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This question was not discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
The French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. to increase it to well over 100 billion euros.
Given the fact that the exchange of goods between 2000 and 2007 had increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this goal is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into an agreement, so that in the future air transport will also be promoted.
India wants to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to strike a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India’s number one partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among the EU partners.
The summit was devoted to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference was also urged.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides to blame for the failure.
The EU stressed that it adheres to its energy and climate programme, which means that emissions of pollutants should be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India agreed, as well as the proposal to make a kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be addressed, and both sides support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, orders are expected to be placed on French companies worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to the agency reports, the agreement is expected to be concluded for 15 years.
