Billionaire Steve Fossett's Missing Small Plane Reunited A Year Ago
Steve Fossett's small plane, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, was found.
The items have been found on a high plateau of 3000 m altitude, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
There were no human remains inside the plane, however.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely dispelled the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, and a troop has been dispatched. Now we are certain that it is the plane that Steve Fossett flew with on the day of his disappearance."
Mr Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found in or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Transportation Safety (NTSB) noted that just hours after the aircraft was sighted, a team was dispatched to identify the aircraft: the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett in Yerington, Nevada, began a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, some of Fossett’s personal belongings were also found in California, near the border with Nevada, by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two IDs with the name Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had taken a place in history through a long series of records.
In 2002, he was the first person to circle the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he circled the world in a single non-stop flight by plane.
Among his numerous records is also an altitude flight of 15445 m above the Andes, but this one with a co-pilot.
